  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent money laundering. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verify customer identities\n- Assess customer risk profiles\n- Monitor suspicious transactions\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- File Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Report large cash transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Compliance Programs\n- Develop internal policies and procedures\n- Conduct regular risk assessments\n- Implement employee training programs\n\n4. Know Your Customer (KYC) Regulations\n- Collect detailed customer information\n- Perform background checks\n- Verify source of funds\n\n5. Regulatory Compliance\n- Follow laws like the Bank Secrecy Act\n- Comply with international AML standards\n- Subject to potential audits and penalties\n\n6. Transaction Monitoring\n- Use automated systems to detect unusual patterns\n- Flag potentially suspicious transactions\n- Investigate and report potential money laundering activities\n\nFinancial institutions can face significant legal and financial penalties for non-compliance with these obligations.",
